post_text:
FRHSD is holding four general information question-and-answer sessions about the Magnet Programs and International Baccalaureate. Parents, guardians, and students of the Class of 2025 (current 8th graders) are invited to attend. These are optional and not required in order to apply. Join us on any of the following dates: September 15 @ 4:00 PM, September 17 @ 7:00 PM, September 21 @ 4:00 PM, or September 23 @ 7:00 PM.

Visit www.frhsd.com to access links to the sessions and to submit questions ahead of time.

post_text:
Dear Freehold Regional Community,

Today, Governor Murphy released guidance to school districts to aid in the planning of in-person graduation ceremonies after July 6th. We are happy to report that we can proceed as planned and will host in-person ceremonies the week of July 27th. Our virtual graduation ceremony will still be held on June 24th to allow students who may not be able to attend the in-person event to receive recognition.

With this new guidance providing an increased number of individuals allowed at outdoor gatherings, we will ensure that the Class of 2020 has a special and meaningful graduation. Principals will communicate the details of both the virtual and in-person ceremonies as each program nears.

Sincerely,

Charles B. Sampson, Ed.D.
text:
Dear Freehold Regional Community,

Today, Governor Murphy released guidance to school districts to aid in the planning of in-person graduation ceremonies after July 6th. We are happy to report that we can proceed as planned and will host in-person ceremonies the week of July 27th. Our virtual graduation ceremony will still be held on June 24th to allow students who may not be able to attend the in-person event to receive recognition.

With this new guidance providing an increased number of individuals allowed at outdoor gatherings, we will ensure that the Class of 2020 has a special and meaningful graduation. Principals will communicate the details of both the virtual and in-person ceremonies as each program nears.

Sincerely,

Charles B. Sampson, Ed.D.

post_text:
If you’re out driving along Route 9 and Route 79 make sure you take a look at the billboards alongside the road.

The Freehold Regional Education Association has purchased three billboards to send a special message to students of the Freehold Regional High School District. The group was able to purchase the billboards thanks to a grant program through the New Jersey Education Association.

The signs will appear at the following intersections:
Route 9 by Schibanoff Road
Route 9 by Strickland Road
Route 79 by Ryan Road

“With the Class of 2020 missing out on so much of their senior year, we wanted to congratulate them in an extra special way. We also wanted all students across the district to know how much we love and miss them. We cannot wait until we are back in the classroom with them again,” Sarah Reichenbecher, President of FREA said.

Check out the billboard below!
text:
If you’re out driving along Route 9 and Route 79 make sure you take a look at the billboards alongside the road.

The Freehold Regional Education Association has purchased three billboards to send a special message to students of the Freehold Regional High School District. The group was able to purchase the billboards thanks to a grant program through the New Jersey Education Association.

The signs will appear at the following intersections:
Route 9 by Schibanoff Road
Route 9 by Strickland Road
Route 79 by Ryan Road

“With the Class of 2020 missing out on so much of their senior year, we wanted to congratulate them in an extra special way. We also wanted all students across the district to know how much we love and miss them. We cannot wait until we are back in the classroom with them again,” Sarah Reichenbecher, President of FREA said.

Check out the billboard below!

Today, Governor Murphy announced that all New Jersey Public Schools will remain closed through the end of the 2019-2020 school year. The Freehold Regional High School District will continue to engage students in Remote Learning during this mandated closure through the end of the school year.

Regardless of our inability to physically convene students within our schools, please know that we are exploring safe and creative processes for graduation for the Class of 2020. The exact details will be communicated with families once finalized.

We recognize that the disruption to student learning, routines, and traditions is challenging for our 10,600 students and families. Please know that the FRHSD faculty and staff are here to support you academically and emotionally during this transition.

post_text:
Dr. Sampson joined other members of the League of Innovative Schools in highlighting the need for Digital Equity.

As the country navigates through a pandemic that has shuttered schools across the nation, the need for all students to have a viable internet connection has become even more evident. While some areas are accustomed to high-speed internet, there are many areas in the United States which do not have that luxury. To highlight this inequity, school officials from coast to coast helped to create a video supporting #ConnectKidsNow.

The Digital Promise League of Innovative Schools connects and rallies the most forward-thinking leaders of the nation’s school districts. The Freehold Regional High School District and Dr. Sampson have been a member of the League since 2015. You can see the video in the link below!

post_text:
The SAT Testing Scheduled for Saturday, March 14 in the Freehold Regional High School District Has Been Cancelled

Due to concerns regarding the COVID-19 outbreak affecting nearby communities, the SAT administrations scheduled for Saturday, March 14 at Freehold High School, Howell High School, and Marlboro High School have been cancelled. The College Board will notify students who have registered for this test session, via email, of the cancellation. As we are unable to schedule make-up testing, all registered students will receive test fee refunds.

The next two Saturday SAT test dates are May 2, 2020, and June 6, 2020. Both Freehold High School and Howell High School will serve as testing sites on those dates. Additionally, statewide, on May 2, there are 201 testing sites; on June 6, there are 180 testing sites. Please check your College Board account for additional details and to register for a future SAT administration in May and/or June, 2020. Please email your school counselor with any questions regarding SAT registration.

post_text:
Marlboro High School senior Hailey Steinberg has been named one of more than 4,500 candidates in the 2020 U.S. Presidential Scholars Program. The candidates were selected from nearly 3.6 million students expected to graduate from U.S. high schools this year.

Inclusion in the U.S. Presidential Scholars Program is one of the highest honors bestowed upon graduating high school seniors. Scholars are selected on the basis of superior academic and artistic achievements, leadership qualities, strong character and involvement in community and school activities. A distinguished panel of educators will review these submissions and select approximately 600 semifinalists in early April. The Commission on Presidential Scholars will select the finalists, and the U.S. Department of Education will announce the Scholars in May. We're rooting for you Hailey!

post_text:
Actor Tom Pelphrey recently returned to the halls of Howell High School during a workshop session with students in the Fine & Performing Arts Magnet Program. Mr. Pelphrey, a 2000 graduate of the Fine & Performing Arts Magnet Program, has appeared in Netflix’s "Iron Fist," CBS’s "Guiding Light" and "As the World Turns," and recently signed on to be a regular cast member in Netflix’s "Ozark."

In a workshop style session, Mr. Pelphrey guided students in both the acting and the entertainment technology tracks. Students prepared scenes ahead of time to work on that day. Mr. Pelphrey watched the scenes and provided tweaks and feedback on ways to alter them. The experience was to show students how a director would provide guidance in a real-world situation.

post_text:
As you are aware, the Freehold Regional's state funding was reduced by $3.8 million this year. Next year we will lose between $6 and $7 million with subsequent reductions for the next four years thereafter continuing until we lose approximately $30 million in funding.

The impact of a revenue loss of this magnitude cannot be overstated. Over the next several years, programs and services in the areas of student supports, academic offerings, athletic and extracurricular opportunities, bussing, as well as progress towards targeted refinements outlined in our strategic plan, will all be markedly diminished.

We ask you to consider signing this petition to encourage Governor Murphy and New Jersey Legislators to re-examine this flawed funding formula and delay the phase-in until the full scope of its impact is understood.

post_text:
The Student Transition Employment Program (STEP) at Manalapan High School raised $2,318 for Feed All God's Children, a non-profit organization that operates a soup kitchen in downtown Freehold every Monday, Wednesday, and Thursday.

Students and staff members from Manalapan visited the lunch program, located in the Parish Hall of St. Peter’s Episcopal Church, on December 9th. Students presented the check to Jim Benedict, who runs the non-profit, and then helped serve for the entire lunch period.

Manalapan’s students have raised money for the group the past four years, but this year’s fundraising total was the highest they have ever collected. Way to go!

The holiday season is a time for giving back, a notion that staff members in the Freehold Regional High School District fully embrace. Staff from across the school district recently partnered with Shoes that Fit to deliver new athletic shoes to 50 deserving students.

The Freehold Regional Education Association, Freehold Regional Custodial and Maintenance Association, Freehold Regional Academic Supervisors Association, and Freehold Regional Principals Association joined forces to raise the funds to purchase shoes for students. After their successful fundraising efforts, staff identified students in need and provided them with new shoes in time for the winter.

post_text:
Please take a moment to read Karen Wall’s article about the secretive math surrounding the state’s school funding formula. This article highlights administrators’ frustrations over the lack of transparency regarding the funding cuts we face under S2.

According to the state’s multipliers, if you owned a house valued at $400,000 and earned $100,000 in 2009 you had the ability to pay $4,127 in FRHSD taxes. Keeping that property value and income flat, in 2020 the state’s formula says you’re able to pay $5,396 in FRHSD taxes. How is it possible that the amount of taxes you’re able to pay increased while your salary and home value didn’t? That’s what we and other districts affected by S2 want to know. The numbers just do not add up.

We urge you to reach out and ask your state representatives to re-examine this flawed formula.

PATCH.COM
